    {
      "id": "section-learning-title",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 55,
      "y": 670,
      "width": 560,
      "height": 28,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#f77f00",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "text": "📚  ADR-004: Learning Design",
      "fontSize": 18,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "📚  ADR-004: Learning Design",
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "learning-content",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 55,
      "y": 708,
      "width": 560,
      "height": 390,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "text": "Decision: SM-2 Spaced Repetition (not Leitner boxes)\nReason: SM-2 is the most evidence-backed SRS algorithm (basis of Anki).\nEase factor per card personalises scheduling. Leitner is simpler but\nless optimal. Same algorithm used by millions of language learners.\n\nDecision: Grammar-explicit teaching (vs Duolingo implicit)\nReason: Duolingo hides grammar rules hoping pattern recognition emerges.\nResearch (skill acquisition theory) shows explicit rule instruction +\npractice is significantly faster for adult learners with literacy.\nEach lesson: rule → paradigm table → 20+ exercises on that rule.\n\nDecision: Vocabulary + grammar interleaved (not isolated)\nReason: When teaching food vocabulary, simultaneously drill accusative case\n(ich möchte einen Kaffee). Never introduce vocab without grammatical context.\nThis halves the time needed to internalize both concepts.\n\nDecision: Quality sessions over login streaks\nReason: Duolingo streaks reward app-opening, not learning. Quality session\nrequires: 15+ min active OR 10+ SRS cards reviewed OR 1+ lesson completed.\nThis means the streak number is a real signal of learning, not gamification.\n\nDecision: A1 → B1 in 26 weeks (aggressive but realistic)\nReason: Standard CEFR estimate for motivated adult with daily study:\n~150-200 hours for A1→B1. At 30 min/day × 26 weeks = 91 hours.\nHigher density than standard courses compensates. Achievable with consistency.",
      "fontSize": 14,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Decision: SM-2 Spaced Repetition (not Leitner boxes)\nReason: SM-2 is the most evidence-backed SRS algorithm (basis of Anki).\nEase factor per card personalises scheduling. Leitner is simpler but\nless optimal. Same algorithm used by millions of language learners.\n\nDecision: Grammar-explicit teaching (vs Duolingo implicit)\nReason: Duolingo hides grammar rules hoping pattern recognition emerges.\nResearch (skill acquisition theory) shows explicit rule instruction +\npractice is significantly faster for adult learners with literacy.\nEach lesson: rule → paradigm table → 20+ exercises on that rule.\n\nDecision: Vocabulary + grammar interleaved (not isolated)\nReason: When teaching food vocabulary, simultaneously drill accusative case\n(ich möchte einen Kaffee). Never introduce vocab without grammatical context.\nThis halves the time needed to internalize both concepts.\n\nDecision: Quality sessions over login streaks\nReason: Duolingo streaks reward app-opening, not learning. Quality session\nrequires: 15+ min active OR 10+ SRS cards reviewed OR 1+ lesson completed.\nThis means the streak number is a real signal of learning, not gamification.\n\nDecision: A1 → B1 in 26 weeks (aggressive but realistic)\nReason: Standard CEFR estimate for motivated adult with daily study:\n~150-200 hours for A1→B1. At 30 min/day × 26 weeks = 91 hours.\nHigher density than standard courses compensates. Achievable with consistency.",
      "lineHeight": 1.4
    },

